<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880606-0087 </DOCNO><HL> Two Canadian Firms Launch Their Offer For Food Distributor </HL><SO> </SO><CO> T.PGI UGO.B EMP.A </CO><IN> TNM </IN><DATELINE> MONTREAL  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Provigo Inc.'s two largest shareholders launched their offer for an additional 10% stake in the food distribution concern at a cost of 91.8 million Canadian dollars (US$74.6 million).    Unigesco Inc. and Empire Co. filed notice of the offer with the Toronto and Montreal stock exchanges. The C$10.75 a share offer would increase the companies' combined stake in Montreal-based Provigo to 51% from 41%.    Provigo closed Friday on the Toronto Stock Exchange at C$10, unchanged. Unigesco and Empire announced plans for the bid last week.    Unigesco is a Montreal-based holding concern while Empire Co., based in Stellarton, Nova Scotia, is a supermarket and real estate company controlled by the Sobey family. The two companies said that they agreed to a voting trust agreement covering their joint stake in Provigo.    Unigesco currently holds a 21% stake in Provigo while Empire Co. holds a 20% stake. If their planned bid is successful, Unigesco would hold a 26% stake in Provigo and Empire a 25% stake. </TEXT></DOC>